{
  "stem": "27509.9",
  "chunk_idx": 7,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 10.4,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 13,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "I always looked forwards, in the sense that I didn't let whatever-- no matter how it ate my soul, how the tragedy has affected me-- all my family was wiped out.",
      "word_count": 31
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 13,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "The community was wiped out.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 13,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 4,
      "text": "The people and-- but I was always looking at tomorrow from a positive-- the counter force, or the countervailing force, historically, was the establishment of the State of Israel.",
      "word_count": 29
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 13,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 5,
      "text": "It happened at-- almost at the same time.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 13,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 6,
      "text": "And instead of thinking in terms of destruction, I thought in terms of building, instead in terms of creation, creation of the people, of the creation of a new future for our people, and creation of-- of a future for our community, a creation ensuring the existing continuity of new generations of Jews in Australia, which I could make some contribution and so on.",
      "word_count": 64
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 13,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 7,
      "text": "It was always a positive, constructive attitude, even if-- if I had to grapple with the tragedy on a personal basis.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 13,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 8,
      "text": "But it was-- I didn't let that-- that destruction and that tragedy destroy my positive outlook on life and my faith in the future.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 0,
      "text": "Well, maybe if you'll permit me to give you a-- a classical answer from the Bible-- the story of the parting of the Red Sea and the Exodus, as described in the Bible, yes-- where the waters parted and the Jewish people went through on dry land-- the commenter [NON-ENGLISH] makes a-- an extraordinary human observation about that act of-- of a supernatural act of parting of the sea.",
      "word_count": 69
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 1,
      "text": "[NON-ENGLISH] says that the sea did not part until the people went into the water, and the water reached right up to their mouths.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 2,
      "text": "What-- that was allegorical, of course.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 3,
      "text": "What he was trying to say is a very simple truism.",
      "word_count": 11
    }
  ],
